content.text:
Looking at it, `RtiSubscriptionManager` does almost nothing:

```cpp
// rti_subscription_manager.cpp
void set_message_callback(MessageCallback cb) { inner_.set_message_callback(std::move(cb)); }
bool subscribe(const std::string& name, const std::string& /*type*/) { return inner_.subscribe(name); }
bool unsubscribe(const std::string& name) { return inner_.unsubscribe(name); }
void unsubscribe_all() { inner_.unsubscribe_all(); }
```

Every method is a one-liner forwarding to `DdsSubscriptionManager`. The only "logic" is ignoring the `topic_type` parameter in `subscribe()`.

The same is true for `RtiTopicSource` after the simplification -- it's now just:

```cpp
std::vector<TopicInfo> get_topics() { return discovery_.get_topics(); }
std::string get_schema(const std::string& name) { return discovery_.get_schema(name); }
std::string schema_encoding() const { return kSchemaEncodingOmgIdl; }
```

**You don't need them as separate classes.** `DdsSubscriptionManager` could directly implement `SubscriptionManagerInterface`, and `DdsTopicDiscovery` could directly implement `TopicSourceInterface`. That would eliminate 4 files (2 headers + 2 cpps).

Want me to fold them in?

