## Code Reuse Review: `ros2/` Directory

### Finding 1 — `TopicDiscovery::get_topics()` and `refresh()` are dead code

**`get_topics()` at `ros2/src/topic_discovery.cpp:47`** is never called outside of the tests. The only production caller of `TopicDiscovery` is `Ros2TopicSource::get_topics()` at `ros2/src/ros2_topic_source.cpp:29`, and it calls `topic_discovery_.discover_topics()` directly, bypassing the cached version entirely. A search for `.get_topics()` across all production `.cpp` and `.hpp` files finds zero hits against `TopicDiscovery`; the only file that calls `discovery_->get_topics()` is `tests/unit/test_topic_discovery.cpp:59`.

**`refresh()` at `ros2/src/topic_discovery.cpp:51`** is also never called from production code. No `.cpp` or `.hpp` file outside of `topic_discovery.cpp` itself and the test (`test_topic_discovery.cpp:69`) invokes `refresh()`.

Both methods exist solely to satisfy the test and have no callers in the production code path. The internal `topics_` vector that backs them (`ros2/include/pj_bridge_ros2/topic_discovery.hpp:63`) is populated by `discover_topics()` but read back by nothing in production.

---

### Finding 2 — Duplicate state: `topic_type_cache_` in `Ros2TopicSource` vs. `topics_` in `TopicDiscovery`

`Ros2TopicSource::get_topics()` (`ros2/src/ros2_topic_source.cpp:28–38`) calls `topic_discovery_.discover_topics()`, which already returns the full `vector<TopicInfo>` — each `TopicInfo` contains both `.name` and `.type`. Immediately after, `Ros2TopicSource` rebuilds its own `topic_type_cache_` (an `unordered_map<string, string>`) by iterating that same vector:

```cpp
// ros2/src/ros2_topic_source.cpp:31-35
topic_type_cache_.clear();
for (const auto& topic : topics) {
  topic_type_cache_[topic.name] = topic.type;
}
```

Meanwhile, `TopicDiscovery` keeps an identical `vector<TopicInfo> topics_` (`ros2/include/pj_bridge_ros2/topic_discovery.hpp:63`) as cached state. This means the name→type mapping is stored twice: once as a vector of structs inside `TopicDiscovery`, and once as a hash map inside `Ros2TopicSource`.

`get_schema()` at `ros2/src/ros2_topic_source.cpp:40–47` is the only consumer of `topic_type_cache_`. Since `discover_topics()` already returns all the data needed, `Ros2TopicSource` could eliminate `topic_type_cache_` entirely by iterating the returned `topics` vector directly, or by asking `TopicDiscovery` for its cached `topics_` — except that would give the existing `get_topics()` a real use. Alternatively, `TopicDiscovery` could expose a `get_type(name)` lookup so neither a separate cache nor a redundant iteration is needed.

The concrete duplication: `ros2/include/pj_bridge_ros2/topic_discovery.hpp:63` (`topics_`) and `ros2/include/pj_bridge_ros2/ros2_topic_source.hpp:51` (`topic_type_cache_`) hold the same information in different shapes.

---

### Finding 3 — `SubscriptionInfo::callback` is a write-once, never-read field

In `GenericSubscriptionManager::subscribe()` at `ros2/src/generic_subscription_manager.cpp:40–53`, the passed `callback` is captured into a lambda (`sub_callback`, line 40) that is given to `node_->create_generic_subscription()` (line 45). The field `info.callback = callback` is then stored at line 50, but that value is **never read back** anywhere in the codebase.

Searching every `.cpp` and `.hpp` file in `ros2/` for any use of `info.callback`, `it->second.callback`, or `.callback` against a `SubscriptionInfo` yields only the single assignment at `generic_subscription_manager.cpp:50`. There is no re-subscription path, no callback-forwarding path, and no re-registration that reads `SubscriptionInfo::callback` after it is stored.

The field is therefore a data member that serves no runtime purpose. The declared field in `ros2/include/pj_bridge_ros2/generic_subscription_manager.hpp:62`:

```cpp
struct SubscriptionInfo {
  std::shared_ptr<rclcpp::GenericSubscription> subscription;
  std::string topic_type;
  Ros2MessageCallback callback;   // <-- written once, never read back
  size_t reference_count;
};
```

The actual callback is live only through the `sub_callback` lambda captured inside the `GenericSubscription` (`rclcpp` holds it). The stored copy in `SubscriptionInfo::callback` is superfluous.

---

### Finding 4 — 5 strip functions in `message_stripper.cpp` share an identical structure and could use a template

All five free functions in `ros2/src/message_stripper.cpp` follow exactly this pattern:

```cpp
rclcpp::SerializedMessage strip_X(const rclcpp::SerializedMessage& input) {
  rclcpp::Serialization<MsgType> serializer;
  MsgType msg;
  serializer.deserialize_message(&input, &msg);
  msg.FIELD = SENTINEL;          // ← only this line differs
  rclcpp::SerializedMessage output;
  serializer.serialize_message(&msg, &output);
  return output;
}
```

Specifically:

| Function (line) | Type | Field cleared | Sentinel |
|---|---|---|---|
| `strip_image` (40) | `sensor_msgs::msg::Image` | `msg.data` | `{0}` |
| `strip_compressed_image` (50) | `sensor_msgs::msg::CompressedImage` | `msg.data` | `{0}` |
| `strip_pointcloud2` (60) | `sensor_msgs::msg::PointCloud2` | `msg.data` | `{0}` |
| `strip_laser_scan` (70) | `sensor_msgs::msg::LaserScan` | `msg.ranges`, `msg.intensities` | `{0.0f}` each |
| `strip_occupancy_grid` (81) | `nav_msgs::msg::OccupancyGrid` | `msg.data` | `{0}` |

Four of the five are truly identical modulo the message type. A single function template would handle all four `data`-field cases:

```cpp
template <typename MsgType, auto FieldPtr>
rclcpp::SerializedMessage strip_single_field(
    const rclcpp::SerializedMessage& input,
    typename std::remove_reference_t<decltype(std::declval<MsgType>().*FieldPtr)> sentinel) {
  rclcpp::Serialization<MsgType> s;
  MsgType msg;
  s.deserialize_message(&input, &msg);
  msg.*FieldPtr = sentinel;
  rclcpp::SerializedMessage out;
  s.serialize_message(&msg, &out);
  return out;
}
```

`strip_laser_scan` clears two fields (`ranges` and `intensities`) so it requires a separate specialization or a multi-field variant, but its internal structure is still identical boilerplate. Combining the four identical-field cases would reduce ~36 lines of repetition to a single template instantiation each.

The five boilerplate functions are at `ros2/src/message_stripper.cpp:40`, `50`, `60`, `70`, and `81`. The dispatch table at `ros2/src/message_stripper.cpp:99–115` would not need to change.

---

### Finding 5 — `test_message_buffer.cpp` re-implements `get_current_time_ns()` instead of using the existing utility

`app/include/pj_bridge/time_utils.hpp:27` defines the canonical `get_current_time_ns()`. The test file `tests/unit/test_message_buffer.cpp:52–56` re-implements the identical function as a private test helper method:

```cpp
// tests/unit/test_message_buffer.cpp:52-56
uint64_t get_current_time_ns() {
  auto now = std::chrono::system_clock::now();
  auto duration = now.time_since_epoch();
  return std::chrono::duration_cast<std::chrono::nanoseconds>(duration).count();
}
```

The only difference from the canonical version is the absence of the `static_cast<uint64_t>` (the count is implicitly convertible). This method is then called 14 times within the test file (lines 63, 100, 131, 159, 175, 196, 222, 228, 243, 277, 320, 337, and the `get_current_time_ns()` calls inside test bodies). The test could simply include `"pj_bridge/time_utils.hpp"` and call `pj_bridge::get_current_time_ns()` directly, eliminating the private duplicate.

The canonical implementation at `app/include/pj_bridge/time_utils.hpp:27` is already included by the production code that `test_message_buffer.cpp` tests (`app/src/message_buffer.cpp:22`), so the dependency already exists transitively.

